            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-16T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-16T19:00:00-05:00" n="172" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d172">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 P.W./2–645: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-16T20:00:00-04:00">February 16, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>266. The Department is in agreement with the policy adopted by the Embassy and
                    General Wedemeyer as set forth in the second paragraph of your telegram no. 177,
                    February 6, 2 p.m.</p>
                <p>Questions arising out of the entry into China of French troops or guerillas are,
                    of course, matters to be settled directly by the French and Chinese, but this
                    would not preclude the American military and other authorities from being
                    helpful to the French where feasible and appropriate as, for example, in
                    arranging for supplying medicines. The Chinese should, of course, be informed of
                    any supplies given to the French under such circumstances.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
